  <div class="module-header">&#129302; Module 1 &mdash; ML Foundations (Lessons 1&ndash;4)</div>
  <div class="lesson-card" id="lcard-1" data-lesson="1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(1)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-1">01</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">What is Machine Learning?</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Types of ML, supervised vs unsupervised, key terminology</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-1"><span class="lock-icon">&#128275;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-1">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-1"><h3>Machine Learning — Teaching Computers to Learn</h3>
<p>Machine Learning (ML) is a subset of Artificial Intelligence where systems learn from data and improve their performance without being explicitly programmed for every scenario. Instead of writing rules manually, you show the algorithm examples and it discovers the patterns itself.</p>
<h3>The Three Types of Machine Learning</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Supervised Learning</strong> — The algorithm learns from labelled examples (input + correct output pairs). It learns to map inputs to outputs. Examples: email spam detection, house price prediction, image classification.</li>
<li><strong>Unsupervised Learning</strong> — The algorithm finds patterns in unlabelled data with no correct answers provided. Examples: customer segmentation, anomaly detection, topic modelling.</li>
<li><strong>Reinforcement Learning</strong> — An agent learns by taking actions in an environment and receiving rewards or penalties. Examples: game playing AI, robotics, recommendation systems optimisation.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Key Terminology</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Dataset</strong> — The collection of data used to train and evaluate the model</li>
<li><strong>Feature</strong> — An input variable used to make predictions (age, income, location)</li>
<li><strong>Label</strong> — The output variable the model predicts (spam/not spam, price, category)</li>
<li><strong>Model</strong> — The mathematical function that maps features to predictions</li>
<li><strong>Training</strong> — The process of adjusting model parameters using the training dataset</li>
<li><strong>Inference</strong> — Using a trained model to make predictions on new unseen data</li>
</ul>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Supervised learning</strong> — Learning from labelled examples with known correct outputs<br>
<strong>Unsupervised learning</strong> — Finding patterns in unlabelled data<br>
<strong>Reinforcement learning</strong> — Learning through rewards and penalties from environment interaction<br>
<strong>Feature</strong> — An input variable used to make predictions
