  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-2" data-lesson="2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(2)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-2">02</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">The ML Workflow</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Data collection cleaning EDA feature engineering train/test split</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-2"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-2">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-2"><h3>The End-to-End ML Pipeline</h3>
<p>Building an ML model is not just about choosing an algorithm. The data preparation steps that come before training often determine success or failure more than the algorithm itself. Garbage in, garbage out — poor data produces poor models regardless of sophistication.</p>
<h3>1. Problem Definition</h3>
<p>Clearly define: what are you predicting? What is the input? What counts as success? A vague problem produces an unmeasurable model.</p>
<h3>2. Data Collection</h3>
<p>Gather data from databases, APIs, web scraping, surveys, or public datasets. Volume matters: more data generally means better models, especially for deep learning.</p>
<h3>3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)</h3>
<p>Understand your data before modelling: distribution of values, missing data, outliers, correlations between features and the label. Tools: Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn.</p>
<h3>4. Data Cleaning</h3>
<ul>
<li>Handle missing values: drop rows, fill with mean/median/mode, or predict missing values</li>
<li>Remove or cap outliers</li>
<li>Fix inconsistent categories ("Lagos" and "LAGOS" are the same city)</li>
<li>Remove duplicate rows</li>
</ul>
<h3>5. Feature Engineering</h3>
<p>Create new features that better capture the underlying patterns. Encode categorical variables (one-hot encoding), scale numerical features (normalisation, standardisation), extract date components (day of week, month).</p>
<h3>6. Train/Test Split</h3>
<p>Split data into training set (80%) and test set (20%). Train on the training set. Evaluate on the test set — data the model has never seen. This gives an honest estimate of real-world performance.</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>EDA</strong> — Exploratory Data Analysis: understanding data before modelling<br>
<strong>Feature engineering</strong> — Creating new input variables from existing ones<br>
<strong>Train/test split</strong> — Dividing data into training and evaluation sets<br>
<strong>One-hot encoding</strong> — Converting categorical variables to binary columns
