  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-3" data-lesson="3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(3)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-3">03</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Common ML Algorithms</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Linear regression, decision trees, random forest, k-means, neural networks</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-3"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-3">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-3"><h3>Choosing the Right Algorithm</h3>
<p>Different algorithms suit different problems. Understanding the strengths and weaknesses of common algorithms helps you choose the right tool for each task.</p>
<h3>Regression Algorithms (Predict a Number)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Linear Regression</strong> — Predicts a continuous value by fitting a straight line through the data. Simple, interpretable, fast. Works when relationship is approximately linear.</li>
<li><strong>Polynomial Regression</strong> — Extension of linear regression for curved relationships</li>
</ul>
<h3>Classification Algorithms (Predict a Category)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Logistic Regression</strong> — Despite the name, it classifies. Predicts probability of belonging to a class. Binary or multi-class.</li>
<li><strong>Decision Tree</strong> — Splits data based on feature values in a tree structure. Very interpretable — you can trace exactly why a prediction was made.</li>
<li><strong>Random Forest</strong> — An ensemble of many decision trees. Reduces overfitting. One of the most reliable general-purpose algorithms.</li>
<li><strong>SVM (Support Vector Machine)</strong> — Finds the optimal boundary between classes. Excellent for high-dimensional data.</li>
<li><strong>K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN)</strong> — Classifies based on the majority class of the K closest training examples.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Clustering (Unsupervised)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>K-Means</strong> — Partitions data into K clusters by minimising distance to cluster centres. Simple and fast.</li>
<li><strong>DBSCAN</strong> — Density-based clustering. Finds clusters of arbitrary shape. Handles outliers well.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Neural Networks</h3>
<p>Multilayer networks of interconnected nodes inspired by the brain. Excel at complex pattern recognition: images, audio, text. Require large amounts of data and compute. The foundation of modern AI.</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Classification</strong> — Predicting which category an input belongs to<br>
<strong>Regression</strong> — Predicting a continuous numerical value<br>
<strong>Ensemble</strong> — Combining predictions from multiple models<br>
<strong>Random Forest</strong> — An ensemble of decision trees that reduces overfitting
