  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-4" data-lesson="4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(4)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-4">04</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Model Evaluation and Overfitting</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Accuracy, precision, recall, F1, confusion matrix, bias-variance</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-4"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-4">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-4"><h3>How Do We Know If a Model is Good?</h3>
<p>A model that performs well on training data but fails on new data is useless. Proper evaluation measures real-world performance — how well the model generalises to data it has never seen.</p>
<h3>Classification Metrics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Accuracy</strong> — Correct predictions / total predictions. Misleading for imbalanced datasets (99% not-fraud accuracy is meaningless if only 1% of transactions are fraud).</li>
<li><strong>Precision</strong> — Of all predicted positives, what fraction are actually positive? High precision = few false alarms.</li>
<li><strong>Recall (Sensitivity)</strong> — Of all actual positives, what fraction did we correctly identify? High recall = catching most of the positives.</li>
<li><strong>F1 Score</strong> — Harmonic mean of precision and recall. Balances both. Better for imbalanced datasets than accuracy.</li>
<li><strong>Confusion Matrix</strong> — A table showing True Positives, True Negatives, False Positives, and False Negatives.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Regression Metrics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>MAE (Mean Absolute Error)</strong> — Average absolute difference between predicted and actual</li>
<li><strong>RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)</strong> — Penalises large errors more than MAE</li>
<li><strong>R² (R-squared)</strong> — Proportion of variance explained by the model (1.0 = perfect)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Overfitting and Underfitting</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Overfitting</strong> — The model memorises the training data including noise. High training accuracy, low test accuracy. Fix: more data, regularisation, simpler model, cross-validation.</li>
<li><strong>Underfitting</strong> — The model is too simple to capture patterns. Low accuracy on both training and test data. Fix: more complex model, more features.</li>
</ul>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Overfitting</strong> — Model memorises training data but fails to generalise to new data<br>
<strong>Precision</strong> — Fraction of predicted positives that are actually positive<br>
<strong>Recall</strong> — Fraction of actual positives that were correctly identified<br>
<strong>F1 Score</strong> — Harmonic mean of precision and recall
