  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-7" data-lesson="7"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(7)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-7">07</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">ML in Production</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">MLOps, model serving, monitoring, drift, versioning</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-7"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-7">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-7"><h3>From Notebook to Production</h3>
<p>Most ML tutorials end when the model achieves good test accuracy. But deploying and maintaining a model in production — where it serves real users and continues working over time — is a completely different challenge. MLOps (Machine Learning Operations) addresses this gap.</p>
<h3>Model Serving</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>REST API</strong> — Wrap your model in a Flask or FastAPI endpoint. Accept input data as JSON, return predictions as JSON.</li>
<li><strong>Batch prediction</strong> — Run predictions on large datasets offline on a schedule.</li>
<li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — Low-latency online serving for applications where response speed matters.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Model Versioning</h3>
<p>Track model versions with MLflow or similar tools. When you retrain a model, version it — so you can compare performance, roll back to a previous version if a new one underperforms, and audit which model made which predictions.</p>
<h3>Model Monitoring and Drift</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Data drift</strong> — The statistical distribution of input features changes over time. The model was trained on 2023 data; 2025 data has different patterns.</li>
<li><strong>Concept drift</strong> — The relationship between features and label changes. What predicted fraud in 2023 may not in 2025 as fraud patterns evolve.</li>
<li><strong>Performance monitoring</strong> — Track model accuracy over time. Set alerts when performance drops below a threshold.</li>
</ul>
<h3>The MLOps Pipeline</h3>
<p>Data → Feature Engineering → Training → Evaluation → Versioning → Deployment → Monitoring → Retraining (loop)</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>MLOps</strong> — Practices combining ML engineering and DevOps for production ML systems<br>
<strong>Data drift</strong> — Change in input data distribution over time degrading model performance<br>
<strong>Model versioning</strong> — Tracking and managing different trained versions of a model<br>
<strong>Model serving</strong> — Making a trained model available to process requests in production
